.TH SPM\-SYNC 8 "June 2026" "spm 0.1.0" "System Manager's Manual"
.SH NAME
spm\-sync \- Import foreign packages into the spm database
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B spm sync
[\fB\-\-files\fR] [\fB\-\-prune\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Import packages from the system's native package manager (dpkg or rpm)
into the spm database.  This allows spm to track and manage packages
that were installed through foreign package managers.
.P
Without any flags, \fBspm sync\fR imports metadata only: package names,
versions, and format information are recorded.  Installed file records
are not imported by default.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-\-files\fR
Also import file records for each foreign package.  This enables
complete file-level tracking within spm.
.TP
\fB\-\-prune\fR
Remove spm database entries for foreign packages that are no longer
installed on the system.  This keeps the database consistent with the
underlying package manager's state.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP \(bu 2
\fBspm sync\fR
Import metadata for all foreign packages.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBspm sync \-\-files\fR
Import metadata with file tracking.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBspm sync \-\-prune\fR
Clean up stale entries for removed foreign packages.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR spm (8),
.BR spm\-fsck (8),
.BR spm\-init (8)
